&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Written evidence submitted by [bold]Professor Colin Talbot[bold]Professor of Government, University of Manchester (FTF 07)[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]SPENDING REVIEWS, BUDGETS AND
[normal] FIXED-
[normal]TERM PARLIAMENTS
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]This submission will address one specific aspect of the Inquiry
[normal] terms of reference
[normal]: 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]“The Spending Review announced in June 2013 covers the 2015/16 financial year only. What discussions can take place in the final year of the current Parliament to prepare
[normal] for the next Spending Review?
[normal] 
[normal]What scope is there for future Spending Reviews to more closely mirror the term of a Parliament?”
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The submission will widen the scope slightly of this question, to include how Spending Reviews and the whole Finance and Suppl
[normal]y system might be impacted by the changes introduced by the FTP Act.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]SPENDING REVIEWS AND BUDGETS
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]It is 
[normal]very 
[normal]important to be clear about the status of Spending Reviews. They are simply ‘statements of intent’ by the government, in effect 
[normal]they have
[normal] the sam
[normal]e status as a White Paper. They are not authorised by Parliament and, apart from the short-lived Fiscal Responsibility Act of Feb 2010
[normal], Spending Reviews had no legal basis or force.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Each SR only attains real force when it is implemented through subsequen
[normal]t annual Budgets
[normal]. One problematic issue has been that Budgets – and subsequent Supply motions – do not always follow what was set out in the Spending Review for the relevant year. Moreover Governments do not make it clear when they are deviating from the p
[normal]lan set out in the preceding Spending Review.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]In the latter years of the Labour government, and under the Coalition, this situation has become even more complicated as governments have increasingly used the Pre Budget Report (or ‘Autumn Statement’) to mak
[normal]e changes to both tax and spending policies
[normal], increasingly looking like a mini-budget
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]As 
[normal]Alistair Darling, Chancellor of the Exchequer from 2007 to 2010, remarks that “during my time as Chancellor I had to deliver what were in effect six Budgets”
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]SPENDING REVIEWS – THE STORY SO FAR
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]On its election in 1997 the New Labour Government announced it was introducing multi-year ‘Spending Reviews’, the first of which would be published 
[normal]in the following year
[normal] (1998)
[normal]. These would provide the public spending 
[normal]framework for a 3-year period ahead.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The aims of this innovation were several:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The idea of Governments adopting a medium-term expenditure framework 
[normal]is not 
[normal]especially 
[normal]new –
[normal] the World Bank and IMF had
[normal] been promoting this idea to developing countries for many years before the UK decided to experiment with 
[normal]it. However few OECD countries had adopted such a reform at the time and there was therefore a great
[normal] deal of interest in the British experiment.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]As promised, Labour duly published its first “Comprehensive Spending Review”
[normal] in J
[normal]uly 1998, setting out departmental budgets for the next three fiscal years (1999-2000 to 2001-02).
[normal] Since then there have been si
[normal]x further Spending Reviews, four under Labour and two under the Coalition. These are set out in 
[normal]Figure 
[normal]1
[normal]).
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Figure [bold]1[bold] The History of Spending [bold]Reviews[bold]Spending review – 
[normal]year
[normal] of publication
[normal]Period covered (fiscal years
[normal]*
[normal])
[normal]Number of years - proposed
[normal]Number of years - actual
[normal]1998
[normal]1999-2001
